<font color="#FF0000">CAN'T MAKE IT STOP,DON'T WANT2</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov  3  2:23:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am here because others are not. There are many that I know made it back because I was there. I shudder to think how many would have been killed had I not been there. <br>
I rejoice, knowing that many of them have given life to sons and daughters because I took a chance, and  because of that they made it back, of this I am proud. For this I thank God. That knowledge makes all my memories, hurts, pains and sorrows of no consequences. Except that to allow me to honor life.<br><br>
I saw the Movie, Seven years in Tibet tonight, flashbacks galore, hearing the Chinese radio broadcasts brought back those memories of the nights when Hanoi Hannah would call us out to play, call out our names as well as the names of those who had died the day before by name, rank and serial number.  <br><br>
Yes, we were there for a purpose and I’ve often wondered whose father I killed and who was not born because I killed their father. But it rains on the good as well as the bad and we all get wet and we all go to the bathroom the same way, Big men and small men, men of high rank and those who dig ditches we are all the same. <br><br>
Some will live and some will die, some will laugh and some will cry, we all suffer pain, within and silent, or outwardly and loud. But the lost is no different. The gain is what we must honor with our time.<br>

<p><code>-- cookbarela@iname.com  (Sparrowhawk) </code><p>


